		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> The Anti-Trust<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.31)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10894'>Alex "Worlds" Weavers</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10894&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> August 14, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Virtually every deck that I&#8217;ve seen posted on Decktech recently has been a Trust Me as You Once Did deck.  Now, once Trust is on the table, it&#8217;s very hard to defeat this deck, because the G-Man has ridiculous vitality and Strength of Spirits to make everyone strength +3 out the wazoo.  CAN ANYONE STOP THE MADNESS?<br />
<br />
Yes.  We begin dismantling the Trust deck by examining the fundamentals of Trust Me as You Once Did.<br />
<br />
First of all, Trust Me as You Once Did is a condition.  It can therefore be discarded.  While Moria and Nazgul have no serious condition removal, the other two shadow cultures do.  Isengard has Saruman&#8217;s Power, which is great in any deck, and gets rid of annoying other conditions, like Last Alliance, Gondor Bowmen, and No Strangers to the Shadows.  For Sauron, Shadow&#8217;s Reach is great for knocking out Trust, and it allows you to keep your own conditions.<br />
<br />
Secondly, it requires an exertion on Gandalf.  Therefore, cards that prevent healing of said exertion are great!  Black Breath is great for this, however, if it&#8217;s on the table, then odds are Gandalf is not getting assigned to a skirmish.  You can, however, use Toldea and a few burdens to force Gandalf to skirmish, and then drop the Black Breaths all over him.  In order to Sleep, Caradhras those conditions, the G-Man must discard Trust, and exert Gandalf - it&#8217;s a win-win situation.<br />
<br />
Sauron has a similar card - You Bring Great Evil - very useful when played at the site before a sanctuary.  This card prevents the healing of the 3-4 exertions Gandalf has taken in the run through Moria.  There&#8217;s no way to heal the G-Man in the entire Gandalf culture, so those wounds will probably stick for the rest of the game.  Also in Sauron, Hate and Exert-to-Wound minions go well to prevent single exertions, or to kill Gandalf completely if several are used at once.<br />
<br />
For Uruk-Hai, don&#39;t worry about how they&#39;ll be taking the wounds off of Gandalf, worry about putting them on.  Since Gandalf can&#8217;t bear Armor, this is easy!  Who do you need for the job?  Gandalf&#8217;s old rival, Saruman!  Common version.  For, alas, if Gandalf resists the temptation to be assigned to a skirmish, he takes exertions.  If not, he either takes 2 or exerts to boost himself, either being fine.  If Common Saruman wasn&#8217;t enough, try this combo:  Saruman pops out, along with an Uruk Beserker.  You&#8217;re playing with Eregion Hills, and/or your opponent used Prancing Pony to grab Aragorn.  He has 3 burdens (maybe 1 more from Worry, or a bid of 1), with G-Man, Aragorn, and a few other guys on the table.  You drop Can You Protect Me From Yourself.  Now, he has a choice.  Exhaust Aragorn, or let the Beserker exhaust Gandalf.  Either way, Saruman exerts to place the Beserker on whoever just was exhausted.  Toss in Saruman&#8217;s Power (total 12 shadow, and Gandalf decks are famous for excessive twilight), and you can easily kill whoever was just exhausted, taking out a cornerstone of their deck, or at least a very large brick.  Another good card to play with the rare version of Saruman and a bunch of beastly minions is Saruman&#8217;s Snows.  Powerful fierce guys vs. no pumping = massive wounds.<br />
<br />
Moria Swarms aren&#8217;t all too powerful against Trust, but if you can get enough minions on Frodo, you can occasionally win a game with them.  Remember - they&#8217;ll be reluctant to use Sleep, and Deep in Thought will give you enough shadow to play 2 more minions anyway, so don&#8217;t worry too much about your conditions being discarded.<br />
<br />
In conclusion, Trusting Gandalf may be wise, but learning how to deny it is key.  Peace. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=3969&view=1&PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
